# =============================================================================
#  .gitignore — Real-World E-Commerce DevOps Project on AWS EKS with Terraform
# =============================================================================
#  Purpose:
#    Prevent sensitive, machine-specific, and auto-generated files from being
#    committed to version control. Each section below explains WHAT is ignored
#    and WHY — so future contributors understand the rationale and can make
#    informed decisions before un-ignoring anything.
#
#  Rule of thumb:
#    If a file contains secrets, local state, machine-specific config, or can
#    be regenerated from source — it does NOT belong in Git.
# =============================================================================


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1. Terraform — Working Directories & Provider Plugins
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# The `.terraform/` directory is created by `terraform init` and contains
# downloaded provider binaries, modules, and backend configuration. It is
# machine-specific, can be hundreds of MB in size, and is fully regenerated
# by re-running `terraform init`. Never commit this.
.terraform/
.terraform.d/


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 2. Terraform — State Files
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# State files contain the *real-world mapping* of your infrastructure,
# including resource IDs, IP addresses, and — critically — any sensitive
# values (passwords, tokens, private keys) that providers wrote into state.
# State MUST live in a remote backend (S3-only with native use_lockfile in this project),
# never in Git. Committing state is one of the most common security incidents
# in IaC projects.
*.tfstate
*.tfstate.*
*.tfstate.backup
terraform.tfstate.backup


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 3. Terraform — Crash Logs
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# When Terraform panics, it writes a `crash.log` containing stack traces and
# possibly sensitive runtime data. These are diagnostic artifacts — share
# them privately with maintainers if needed, but never commit them.
crash.log
crash.*.log


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 4. Terraform — Variable Files (.tfvars)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# `.tfvars` files typically contain environment-specific values: account IDs,
# region overrides, instance sizes, and very often SECRETS such as DB
# passwords, API keys, or private SSH keys. Treat every .tfvars file as
# sensitive by default. If a particular .tfvars file is genuinely safe to
# share (e.g. a non-secret example), un-ignore it explicitly with a negation
# pattern — see `!terraform.tfvars.example` below.
*.tfvars
*.tfvars.json

# Allow committing example/template tfvars so contributors know the schema.
!*.tfvars.example
!*.tfvars.json.example

# Allow per-environment tfvars (no secrets — just non-sensitive config like
# region, VPC CIDR, AZ list). Secrets must come from AWS Secrets Manager,
# never from these files.
!environments/*/*.tfvars


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 5. Terraform — Override Files
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Terraform automatically merges any `override.tf` or `*_override.tf` files
# into the configuration. They are intended for LOCAL experimentation
# (e.g., temporarily switching a backend or pinning a provider). Committing
# them silently changes behaviour for everyone, which is a footgun.
override.tf
override.tf.json
*_override.tf
*_override.tf.json


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 6. Terraform — Lock & Plan Artifacts
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# `.terraform.tfstate.lock.info` is a transient file created during
# `terraform apply` and removed when the operation finishes. It should never
# be committed.
#
# NOTE on `.terraform.lock.hcl` — this file pins provider versions across
# the team and SHOULD normally be committed. We are ignoring it here only
# because module authors prefer flexible version resolution; if you are
# consuming (not authoring) modules, REMOVE the `.terraform.lock.hcl` line.
.terraform.tfstate.lock.info
.terraform.lock.hcl

# Plan output files — may contain the full proposed change set including
# secrets. Treat them like state files.
*.tfplan
*.tfplan.*
tfplan
planout


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 7. Terraform — CLI Configuration
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# These files configure Terraform CLI behaviour (e.g., provider mirrors,
# credentials helpers). They are user/machine-specific and may contain
# tokens for private registries.
.terraformrc
terraform.rc


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 8. Terraform — Optional Outputs (commented by default)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Uncomment if your workflow generates these and you don't want them tracked.
# *.dot          # Output of `terraform graph`
# planout        # Saved plan files


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 9. Cloud Credentials & Secrets
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Anything that looks remotely like a credential, key, or secret. AWS
# credential leaks via Git are a leading cause of cloud account compromise.
# Add new patterns aggressively — better to over-ignore than under-ignore.
*.pem
*.key
*.ppk
*.crt
*.cer
*.p12
*.pfx
*.jks
*.keystore
*.truststore

# AWS-specific
.aws/
aws-credentials
credentials
*.credentials

# Generic secret files
secrets/
secret.*
*.secret
*.secrets


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 10. Environment Files
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# `.env` files commonly hold connection strings, API keys, and feature flags.
# They are local by definition. Provide an `.env.example` instead so
# teammates know which variables to set.
.env
.env.*
*.env
!.env.example


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 11. Kubernetes & Helm — Local Artifacts
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# `kubeconfig` files grant cluster access — never commit them.
# Helm packages are build artifacts produced by `helm package`.
kubeconfig
kubeconfig.*
*.kubeconfig

helm-charts/**/charts/
helm-charts/**/Chart.lock
*.tgz


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 12. Editor & IDE Files
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# These are personal preferences. Each developer's editor config is their
# own; don't impose yours on the team.
.vscode/*
!.vscode/settings.json.example
!.vscode/extensions.json
.idea/
*.iml
*.swp
*.swo
*.workspace
*.code-workspace
*.sublime-project
*.sublime-workspace


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 13. Operating System Junk
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Files that operating systems sprinkle into directories — useless to anyone
# else and noisy in diffs.
.DS_Store
.DS_Store?
._*
.Spotlight-V100
.Trashes
ehthumbs.db
Thumbs.db
desktop.ini
$RECYCLE.BIN/


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 14. Logs & Temporary Files
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Logs are runtime output, not source. Temp files are by definition
# disposable.
*.log
logs/
*.tmp
*.temp
*.bak
*.backup
*.old


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 15. Archives & Binary Artifacts
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Compressed archives and binaries are usually build outputs or credential
# bundles. If you genuinely need to commit one, do so explicitly with
# `git add -f`.
*.zip
*.rar
*.7z
*.tar
*.tar.gz
*.tgz
*.gz
*.exe
*.dll
*.so
*.dylib


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 16. Data Files
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CSVs, dumps, and exports often contain real customer or production data.
# Sample/seed data should live in a clearly-named `examples/` folder and
# be un-ignored explicitly.
*.csv
*.tsv
*.sqlite
*.sqlite3
*.db
*.dump
!examples/**/*.csv


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 17. Python — If You Add Helper Scripts
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Common Python clutter. Safe to remove this section if no Python is used.
__pycache__/
*.py[cod]
*$py.class
.venv/
venv/
.pytest_cache/
.mypy_cache/


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 18. Node — If You Add JS Tooling (e.g., CDK, scripts)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
node_modules/
npm-debug.log*
yarn-debug.log*
yarn-error.log*
.pnpm-debug.log*


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 19. CI/CD Local Caches
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Local caches from running pipelines on your machine.
.act/
.github-actions-cache/


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 20. Project-Specific Ignores
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Add anything specific to this repository below this line.
scratch/
sandbox/
*.draft.md


# =============================================================================
#  End of .gitignore
#  Reminder: Once a sensitive file is committed, removing it later does NOT
#  remove it from Git history. If you suspect a secret has been committed,
#  rotate it immediately and rewrite history with `git filter-repo`.
# =============================================================================
